## Checking and removing columns columns with more than 2% missing values (more than 31 missing values)

column_wise_na = df.isna().sum()

df = df.drop(lst1, axis = 1)
In [5]:
## Dropping the rows with remaining NA values

df = df.dropna()
In [6]:
## Dropping columns with no variance (constant values)

lst2 = df.std()[df.std()==0].index
df = df.drop(lst2, axis = 1)
In [7]:
## Dropping columns with very low coefficient of variation (using absolute coeff of variation or also known as relative std dev)

acv = df.std()/abs(df.mean())
lst3 = acv[acv<0.01].index
df = df.drop(lst3, axis = 1)

## Changing column names for ease of calculations

Columns = df.columns
Columns[:-1]

cols = []
for i in Columns[:-1]:
    a = 'Col_'+i
    cols.append(a)
    
cols.append('Pass')
df.columns = cols
In [12]:
## Removing columns using results from ANOVA. 
## The null hypothesis being the mean value of the attribute in a given column is the same for Pass and Fail cases.
## When p value is less than 0.01 we reject the null hypothesis and therefore keep those columns while dropping the others

cols4removal = []
for i in df.columns[:-1]:
    a = i + " ~ Pass"
    mod = ols(a, data = df).fit()
    aov_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(mod, typ = 2)
    if aov_table['PR(>F)'][0] > 0.01:
        cols4removal.append(i)
        
df = df.drop(cols4removal, axis = 1)

## Trying a Logistic Regression model with K-fold, Shuffle Split, Stratified K fold and Leave one out cross validation techniques

kfold = KFold(n_splits = 10)
ss = ShuffleSplit(n_splits=10, test_size=0.25, random_state= 42)
skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10)
loo = LeaveOneOut()

model = LogisticRegression()


results= cross_val_score(estimator=model, X = X_train, y= y_train, cv = kfold)
print(f"Mean Accuracy on validation KFold :{round(results.mean()*100.0,2)}% and Standard Devation of accuracy {round(results.std()*100.0,2)}%")


results= cross_val_score(estimator=model, X = X_train, y= y_train, cv = ss)
print(f"Mean Accuracy on validation Shuffle Split :{round(results.mean()*100.0,2)}% and Standard Devation of accuracy {round(results.std()*100.0,2)}%")


results = cross_val_score(estimator=model, X = X_train, y= y_train, cv = skf)
print(f"Mean Accuracy on validation Stratified KFold :{round(results.mean()*100.0,2)}% and Standard Devation of accuracy {round(results.std()*100.0,2)}%")


results = cross_val_score(estimator=model, X = X_train, y= y_train, cv = loo)
print(f"Mean Accuracy on validation Leave one out:{round(results.mean()*100.0,2)}% and Standard Devation of accuracy {round(results.std()*100.0,2)}%")


model.fit(X_train,y_train)
print(f'Accuracy of Model on test score is {round(100*model.score(X_test,y_test),2)}%','\n')

In [39]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

pipe_logistic = Pipeline([('scl',StandardScaler()),('LR' , LogisticRegression())])

# Create param grid.

param_grid_logistic = {  'LR__penalty' : ['l1', 'l2'],
                         'LR__C' : np.logspace(-4, 4, 20),
                         'LR__solver' : ['liblinear']}

# Create grid search object

clf_lr = GridSearchCV(pipe_logistic, param_grid = param_grid_logistic, cv = 5, verbose=3, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit on data

best_clf_lr = clf_lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

  1. Logistic Regression (Linear Model)
  2. One Support Vector
  3. One Bagging Ensemble Model - Random Forest
  4. One Boosting Ensemble Model - XGBoost
We can try other models (Bagging, GradientBoosting, Adaboost etc) too but after multiple iterations we saw that the latter 3 perform best.¶
Even Naive Bayes was tried but the results were extremely poor¶
We finally pick the Random Forest Classifier with the identified best parameters because it has the fewest misclassifications on the test set¶

Conclusions¶

The Dataset was huge in terms of the number of features however, using various techniques we can reduce the number of dimensions, While it is tempting to just apply PCA for dimensionality reduction but one can do feature engineering in otherways as well and retain the explainability of the model. Which is what we did in the current problem

While we could use other models as well, I chose to use the different types of classifiers choosing one from each bagging, boosting, SVM, and Logistic Regression I also tried Naive Bayes however, the results were as low as a 57% test accuracy

Overall the SVM model works the best with the least number of classification and hence the final model is made using that. The other models were also close and there is a chance that with a larger parameter grid one of the other models does better.
